1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {[%csl Gc8] The Slav Defence is one of the most solid
options for Black against 1.d4 and part of any strong grandmaster's repertoire.
The main goal is to solve the eternal problem of the light-squared bishop,
keeping the chance of developing it either to f5 or g4. White has many options
to fight for an advantage, but since Black's structure is very stable, the
active options are very limited. The Slav is a nice opening for players that
look for solid set-ups and don't care about playing with patience, improving
his position slowly and collecting small strategic advantages.} 3. cxd5 {
In this first database we will look at the anything but harmless Exchange
Variation. Nowadays, players are looking for playable positions in which you
can keep the game going on and trying to pose practical problems to the
opponent. So, this line has turned into a dangerous weapon for technical
players.} ({I will also examine} 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 $5 {when White tries to
force a Catalan against the Slav} (4. Qc2 {is the Argentinian Variation}) (4.
Qb3 $5)) (3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 {this is a tricky move order used by players who
aim to avoid the strategical battle and force Black to keep the bishop on c8
and go to the semi-slav; in this case,} g6 {is a solid and reliable line,
keeping the chance of developing the light-squared bishop later} ({White's
point is that after} 4... Bf5 $5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7,Gd5] attacks
two pawns, thus forcing the bishop to come back to c8. However, Black can be
brave and ignore the threat} Nc6 $5 7. Qxb7 Bd7 {As we'll see, some strong
grandmasters have proved that Black's compensation for the pawn may be enough
in practice.})) 3... cxd5 4. Nc3 {White has some different move orders, and
although Black should be always fine with correct play, it is important to
understand the differences between these lines.} (4. Bg5 $5 {This kind of
"Trompowsky Variation" against the Slav has gained some popularity in the last
years, and may cause Black some problems if you are not aware of how to play
against it.}) (4. Bf4 {likely transposes after} Nc6) 4... Nf6 5. Bf4 (5. Nf3
Nc6 6. e3 $5 {Another tricky move order!}) 5... Nc6 6. Nf3 {Recently, White
players have preferred to put the knight on f3, which historically used to be
the mainline.} ({White has also the option of} 6. e3 a6 $5 7. Bd3 (7. Rc1 {or})
(7. Be2 {are less played options}) 7... Bg4 8. Nge2 {[%csl Ge2] This set-up
was very popular some years ago, especially after two fine victories for White
in high-level games. (Wang Hao-Caruana and Aronian-Nakamura)}) *

