1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bg5 $5 {This move has gained some popularity
in tournament practice in last years. According to my database, Israeli GM
Nabaty was the first strong player to test it. White's goal is to make normal
moves like о ..f6 or e6 difficult for Black, which may result in unpleasant
decisions to be taken right in the very first moves. I've even played this
move myself in a couple of games, to test its practical potential.} Nc6 5. Nc3
{As the theory of this line is still in development, we need to look for
different ideas and possible new paths.} ({For example} 5. e4 $146 {is a
thematic idea in the mainline, but in this case it is a bit hasty, as Black
has not committed the kingside yet, so it seems harmless.} dxe4 6. d5 (6. Nc3
h6 $1 {I think Black has no reason to accept every gambit line, just because
the computer says the positions are playable, as this is what White aims for.
Instead, it is easier to reach a good position by normal play.} 7. Be3 e6 8.
Nxe4 Nf6 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {[%csl Yd4] Black has a good position because of the
isolated pawn.} 10. a3 Bd6 11. Nf3 O-O 12. Bd3 Rd8 $17) 6... h6 $1 {A useful
intermediate move.} (6... Ne5 7. Qa4+ Nd7 8. Nc3 {Black may face some issues
with his development here.} h6 9. Bf4 Ngf6 10. Rd1 g5 $5 11. Be3 Bg7 12. h4 $1
g4 13. Nge2 O-O 14. Ng3 Nb6 15. Qb3 Bd7 16. Bb5 $44 {White should regain the
e4-pawn, leaving Black with some exposed squares on the kingside.}) 7. Be3 (7.
dxc6 $2 {is simply much better for Black.} Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 hxg5 9. Bb5 Bg4+ 10.
Kc2 O-O-O $19) ({and now} 7. Bf4 {can be answered with} e5 $1 {, which makes a
lot of difference.} 8. Bg3 Nce7 $1 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qxe4 Qc7 $1 {[%csl Gc1]
Black manages to develop his pieces in a good way now.} 11. Nc3 Ng6 12. Nf3 Bd6
{[%cal Yf7f5,Gg8f6] Soon White will face some problems with the advance of
Black's centre, for example} 13. Qc4 Qb6 $1 14. Bd3 N8e7 15. O-O O-O 16. Rfe1
f6 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Ye5,Yf6,Gg3] Black is at least fine, but since the passed
pawn is safely blocked, the g3-bishop looks useless and the mobile centre may
become very strong, I think the second player has already the easier play.})
7... Ne5 8. Nc3 (8. Qa4+ {is also harmless now because of} Bd7 9. Qxe4 Ng4 $1 {
and again Black can develop his pieces in a good way.} 10. Nc3 N8f6 11. Qd3
Nxe3 12. Qxe3 g6 13. Nf3 Bg7 14. Bc4 O-O 15. O-O {[%csl Gd5,Yg7] This position
resembles a good version of the Grunfeld for Black, besides an active
g7-bishop he has the bishop pair and d5 is a target in many lines, for example}
b5 $5 16. d6 $5 exd6 17. Bxb5 Bxb5 18. Nxb5 Rb8 $1 19. Qd3 Qb6 $36) 8... Nf6 9.
Bd4 Ng6 10. Bb5+ (10. Bxf6 {is already easier for Black.} exf6 11. Qa4+ Bd7 12.
Qxe4+ Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Bxe7 14. Nf3 Rc8 $17 {[%cal Ge7b4,Yg6f4]}) (10. Qb3 $2 e5
$1 11. Be3 Bd6 $17) 10... Bd7 11. Qb3 Bxb5 12. Qxb5+ Qd7 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14.
O-O-O {White aims to simply organize the pieces with Nge2-Ng3-Rhe1, regain the
pawn and keep Black with some difficulties in development, but this can be
properly resolved with a nice manoeuvre :} Nh4 $1 15. g3 Nf5 {White can't keep
the "grip" on Black's position anymore.} 16. Bxf6 (16. Be5 $2 Ng4) (16. Nge2
Nxd4 17. Rxd4 g6 18. Nxe4 Rc8+ 19. Kb1 Bg7 $15) 16... exf6 17. Nxe4 Re8 18. Nc3
Bc5 19. Nh3 h5 $15 {Black's position seems already easier thanks to the better
coordination of the pieces.}) 5... f6 $5 {From my experience with this line as
White, most of Black's practical problems start when players keep trying to
develop in "Slav way", and this is a good reason why 4.Bg5 might be an
interesting try over the board. I think that not only in this position but in
similar situations in general, you should simply treat the position over the
board as new and different, with its own ideas and demands. Hence, it makes
sense to try using the placement of White's bishop in your favour, preparing
to fight for the centre with e7-e5 soon.} ({When I first saw this line, in a
brief article by Jeroen Bosch (S.O.S) in New in Chess, I remember one of the
main ideas was that after} 5... Nf6 6. Bxf6 gxf6 7. e3 {he claimed that this
structure resembles that reached in some lines of the Trompowsky, with the
difference that Black is deprived of the typical counterplay in the centre
with c7-c5, giving slightly better prospects for White compared to those
positions. Maybe this is not so dangerous, as even Magnus Carlsen has played
this way as Black, but I remember when I checked Bosch's analysis that I liked
White's chances, at least from a practical point of view.}) 6. Bd2 {The only
way to fight for advantage.} (6. e4 $1 {I give an exclamation mark to this
move for the creativity of White players finding it, but objectively the only
thing that Black needs to remember here is to not become too greedy.} dxe4 $1 (
6... e5 $5 {also worked well for Black.} 7. exd5 Nxd4 8. Be3 Nf5 9. Bd2 Bc5 {
[%cal Yg8e7,Gf5d6] , and Black's development was fine in Harikrishna,P (2744)
-Korobov,A (2652)/Huaian IMSA blitz 2nd 2017 (18)/1/2-1/2.}) (6... fxg5 $6 7.
exd5 Nb8 {I think there are some risks involved in accepting such a sacrifice,
a major one being that you would likely be playing against an engine, as of
course White hardly would offer a piece for a pawn without knowing what is
going on. Here is one example:} 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Nxg5 a6 {Tugarin,A (2267)
-Baghdasaryan,V (2436)/Moscow op-A 14th 2018 (8)/0-1 The check on b5 followed
by Ne6 had to be prevented. Still, White can continue with} 10. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 11.
Qb3 b5 12. Bd3 {Black faces some problems in development here, and if} g6 $2
13. d6 $1 {[%cal Gb3f7] is already much better for White.}) 7. Be3 (7. d5 $2 {
leads to simplifications and a better position for Black.} fxg5 8. dxc6 Qxd1+
9. Rxd1 bxc6 10. Nxe4 g4 $1 {Black is a pawn up and his development is not so
difficult anymore.} 11. Bd3 Nf6 12. Ne2 Rb8 13. b3 e5 14. O-O Bb4 $15) 7... e6
8. Nxe4 (8. Bc4 $5 {Again, Black has no reason to hold on to the pawn with
committal moves like f6-f5, but should just continue his development.} Bb4 {
Dambacher,M (2468)-Van Delft,M (2387)/NED-chT 1718 2017 (9.4)/1/2-1/2} 9. Qg4
$5 Qc7 $1 10. Qxe4 {Black has an interesting idea in this position.} Bxc3+ 11.
bxc3 Na5 $1 12. Bb5+ Bd7 $1 13. Qxe6+ Ne7 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {
despite being a pawn down now, Black has nice squares for both knights and
will exert strong pressure against White's structure in the centre.} 16. Ne2
Nc4 17. Bd2 Rhe8 18. Kd1 Nd5 19. Re1 Re6 20. Kc2 Rae8 $44) 8... Bb4+ $1 $146 {
The most precise move order.} (8... Qa5+ {Sulskis,S (2529)-Balcerak,J (2473)/
BL2-West 1819 2018 (5.2)/1/2-1/2} 9. Nd2 $5 {After Nf3-Bd3-0-0 White can
improve the knight via c4 or b3 with tempo, attacking the queen.}) 9. Nc3 Nge7
10. Nf3 O-O {[%csl Yd4,Ge6] Despite White's attempt to create early
complications, we've reached a normal IQP position. If the pawn were on f7 we
could say that Black has slightly better chances, but here the e6-pawn needs
constant vigilance a well, making the position's evaluation rather balanced.}
11. Bd3 (11. Bc4 $2 {only helps Black to reach an optimal piece placement.} Na5
$1 12. Bd3 b6 13. O-O Bb7 {[%cal Ya8c8,Ge7d5,Ge7f5]}) 11... b6 12. O-O Qd7 $1 {
The e6-pawn forces Black to play carefully.} (12... Bb7 $2 13. Qb3 Qd7 $2 14.
Bc4 $18) 13. Qe2 (13. Qb3 {is not dangerous now, as Black can relieve the
pressure on the e6-pawn:} Kh8 $1 14. Rac1 Bb7 15. Bc4 {now} Bxc3 $1 16. Rxc3
Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5] The e6-pawn is untouchable and Black will follow-up with
