1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 {Although the symmetrical structure
might suggest a boring game, the Exchange Variation has been used by many
strong players in recent years, when they wanted to avoid heavy theory and go
for non-forcing positions. Since White often gets a small edge because of his
small lead in development, this line may be an option for technical, patient
players. White has many different move-orders and set-ups available, and in
this chapter, we will study the rarer ones, which are nonetheless anything but
harmless.} (4. Bf4 {is another move order, which normally transposes.} Nc6 5.
Nc3 Nf6 6. e3) 4... Nf6 (4... Nc6 {allows} 5. e4 $5 {, which is probably not
so dangerous, but I don't see the point of giving White one more possibility.})
