1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 $5 {I remember back when I was a child,
this move was considered to be harmless against the Slav because Black
develops the bishop and gets a "solid Catalan without the bad bishop". This
was more than 10 years ago though, and recently this move gained a lot of
popularity among strong players, as White doesn't seek an advantage from the
very first move, but instead looks for a complicated positional battle in the
middlegame. Another point of this move is that the game may transpose into
other openings, as we shall see.} Bf5 {I would like to suggest two options to
face this line. This is the move to keep the game "Slav style".} ({I checked} 
4... Bg4 $5 {, which seems interesting, but from a practical point of view. I
think after} 5. Bg2 ({Black's idea is to provoke} 5. Ne5 Bf5 {, but I couldn't
find an advantage for White here.}) 5... e6 6. O-O Nbd7 {we have transposed to
a kind of Reti-Catalan where White has plenty of options, so although Black is,
of course, solid, I think playing this way gives much more freedom to the
first player.} 7. Nc3 (7. b3) (7. Qb3) (7. Nbd2) (7. cxd5) (7. h3)) ({But I
like} 4... dxc4 $5 5. Bg2 Nbd7 $1 {The goal here is not necessarily to keep
the pawn, but since it will take White some moves to regain the material,
Black can develop in the meantime.} ({It is possible to play materialistically
as well.} 5... b5 $5 6. O-O Bb7 7. Ne5 e6 {, when the game transposes to the
actual Catalan Opening.} 8. a4 a6 9. b3 $5 {, with a complicated battle ahead.
Practice has shown that White has great compensation for the pawn.}) 6. O-O (6.
a4 {is a clever idea, aiming to attack the pawn and answer Nb6 with a4-a5, so
Black should play} a5) (6. Qc2 {and} Nb6 7. Nbd2 g6 {likely transpose.}) 6...
g6 $1 {With this move we enter Grunfeld territory. I like this way of
development because the bishop seems more useful on the long diagonal than on
its natural square e7, as it helps Black to press White's centre in the future.
White can just play to regain the pawn on c4, but that usually allows Black to
finish his development without problems. The most ambitious ideas for the
first player are related to building a strong centre e4/d4 first and later
recapture the pawn, playing for a space advantage, but this usually leads to
the exchange of one or two pieces, when Black should be also fine.} 7. Qc2 (7.
a4 a5 $1 {Black should secure b6 for the knight.} 8. Na3 {[%csl Ga3] Normally
White prefers the route a3-c4 for this knight, as on d2 it would be in the way
of the dark-squared bishop.} (8. Nc3 {was played in one game, in gambit style.}
Bg7 9. e4 O-O 10. Qe2 Nb6 11. h3 Ne8 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ye8d6,Ye8c7,Yc7d5] A
typical manoeuvre in this line. The knight can go to d6 and even make it
harder for White to regain the pawn c4. Another point is that Black has f7-f5
to weaken White's centre, and in that case also c7-d5 becomes an attractive
route for the knight.} 12. Rd1 f5 $5 13. Bg5 {Klemm,D (2241)-Gauglitz,G (2388)/
BL2-Ost 0708 2007 (9.8)/0-1 After something like} fxe4 14. Nxe4 h6 15. Bd2 Nd6
16. Ne5 Qe8 $1 17. Nc5 Nd5 $13 {[%cal Yb7b6,Gc8f5] the position remains
complex, but Black found some good squares for his pieces in the centre.}) 8...
Nb6 9. Ne5 Be6 $1 {Another nice point of leaving the pawn on e7 is that Black
is able to support c4 with the bishop.} 10. e4 Bg7 11. Be3 {This is an
important moment because White plans either Rc1, regaining the pawn, or f2-f4,
with potential pressure on the kingside. Therefore Black plays} Nfd7 $1 {
, which is good against both ideas.} 12. Nxd7 (12. f4 $6 Nxe5 13. dxe5 {
[%cal Ye3b6,Yf4f5]} Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Nxa4 15. f5 {Black correctly decided to
sacrifice the piece here.} Nxb2 $1 16. fxe6 {Niemi,K (2342)-Puuska,H (1928)/
Naantali Avoin op 2017 (4)/ 1-0 , but the best continuation now was} fxe6 {
, when Black will have at least four (!) pawns for the piece.} 17. Rb1 Bxe5 18.
Bh3 b5 19. Bxe6 Rd8 20. Bf7+ Kd7 21. Bb6 Ra8 $17 {[%csl Ya5,Yb5,Yc4,Yc6][%cal
Gh8b8]}) (12. d5 $2 {looks aggressive but it is just bad.} Nxe5 13. dxe6 Qxd1
14. Rfxd1 Nxa4 $17) 12... Bxd7 13. Rc1 {Fominykh,M (2313)-Yefimov,M (2050)/
Pardubice Czech op-A 21st 2010 (7)/1-0} (13. Qe2 {Rozum,I (2554)-Baghdasaryan,
V (2372)/ Moscow op-A 2015 (6)/1/2-1/2} c3 $5 14. bxc3 Nxa4 15. c4 c5 $1 $132)
