1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 {This move characterizes the Argentine
Variation, a positional line which aims to avoid the main theory and keep some
flexibility in White's development. The obvious goal is to prevent Black from
developing the bishop to f5, but the queen's placement has pros and cons, and
I think the move that better underlines this best is} g6 $1 {[%cal Yc8f5] ,
insisting on developing the bishop to f5. We have seen similar ideas in the
previous chapter, so it is enough to say that the game transposes now into
some Grunfeld-like positions, where the queen is always a little bit misplaced
on c2.} (4... dxc4 {is also seen in a lot of games, with the idea of playing
either Bf5 or Bg4 after 5.Qxc4, but recently} 5. e4 $5 {has gained in
popularity.} b5 6. b3 $1 cxb3 7. axb3 $44 {[%csl Gc6,Yd4,Ye4] For the pawn,
White gets more space in the centre and the possibility of exerting pressure
on Black's queenside. This is, of course, playable for Black, but I think
there's no reason to enter into such a complicated position if you are looking
for a solid approach; also, I should add that I've written a recent article
for Yearbook on this line for White, so I really believe in White's
compensation :)}) 5. Bf4 {White has many options and set-ups available, but
this one is the most popular.} (5. e3 {is a more restrained way of development}
Bg7 6. Bd3 {The advantage of developing the bishop first is to keep the Nb1
flexible.} (6. Nc3 O-O 7. Bd3 {is a more active square for the bishop,
preventing Bf5, but as we have seen, the bishop is more exposed on d3, so
Black can exploit this with} (7. Bd2 {[%cal Ga1c1] As is often the case in
these Grunfeld-Slav positions, White aims for fast development on the
queenside, in order to forestall Black's breakthrough with c6-c5.} a6 $5 {
this kind of prepares the next move, like in the Slav Exchange} 8. Rc1 Bg4 $1
9. Ne5 ({The point is that after} 9. Qb3 Bxf3 {[%cal Ya8a7] Black can defend
the pawn with Ra7, and if} 10. Qxb7 {, the position becomes double-edged.} Nbd7
11. gxf3 e5 $1 {Opening the centre, Black gains a strong initiative.} 12. Qxc6
