1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 $5 {This is another interesting sideline,
and in practice, it has the same goal as the early development of the queen to
c2 (making it harder for Black to develop the light-squared bishop), with the
difference that White does not have to worry about g6 now, since this does not
prepare an attack on the queen. Like in the previous chapter, White has a
flexible position and many ways to bring his pieces into play. Against this
line, I recommend playing "Slav style" with} dxc4 {, a move that was possible
against 4.Qc2 too, but would have allowed the gambit line 4...dxc4 5.e4!?} ({
Some players prefer} 4... e6 {here, opting for a Semi-slav set-up, since the
queen almost never goes to b3 in these positions. I guess it is more a matter
of taste, but as we are dealing with Slav positions, I prefer to keep it
simple.}) 5. Qxc4 Bg4 $5 {After studying this move, I concluded it is both
solid and an interesting fighting option for Black.} (5... Bf5 {is the
classical and most popular move.}) 6. Nbd2 {I was a bit surprised to realize
that this move became the most popular in the last years, but it is a good
sign: White players basically gave up looking for an advantage in unbalanced
positions and decided to fight for it in quiet, positional battles in the
middlegame.} ({As far as I remember,} 6. Nc3 $5 {used to be the main move,
