Although White is playing a bit slowly, this position is not exactly harmless:
He enjoys a bit more space and can prepare to expand in the centre at the
right moment with e2-e4. Also Ne5 is always an idea to be considered and the
queen may face some problems on a6 if White is allowed to play Bf1 at some
point. Black, on the other hand, has a solid position but enjoys less space,
and needs to be careful not to end up in a cramped position. The typical move
to give more freedom to Black's pieces is still c6-c5, but it needs to be
carefully prepared in view of the potential pressure on b7 by White's queen
and bishop. Another way to deal with the lack of space in such positions is to
strive for piece exchanges. Objectively speaking, with correct play by both
sides the position should be balanced.} (12. Re1 {is another normal move.} Rfd8
