1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 {This is a clever move order if White wants
to avoid the complicated battles in the Slav Defense. Black has a wide choice
now, but I think} g6 {is a solid option, which promises good chances of
equalizing. We have seen some Grunfeld-like positions in the previous chapters,
so many ideas can be applied here as well. It is called the Schlechter
Variation and is very popular among Chinese players.} (4... a6 {and}) (4... e6
{are more combative options, but they lead to very complicated positions, and
4...e6 is basically a "different universe" (the Semi-Slav), so I decided to
keep it simple and practical.}) ({White's idea is that after} 4... Bf5 5. cxd5
cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Gd5] there is no easy way for Black to defend both
pawns. We will analyse this position better in the next chapter, as Black has
an interesting option here.}) 5. Nf3 (5. Bd3 Bg7 6. Nge2 {[%csl Ye2] This
set-up hardly poses serious problems for Black.} (6. f4 $6 {[%csl Gf4] is a
typical inaccuracy in such positions. White thinks he is increasing the
control in the centre, but this move only contributes to create weaknesses in
his camp, like the e4-square and the g1-a7 diagonal.} O-O 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. cxd5
cxd5 9. O-O Nb6 10. a4 Bf5 $1 11. Bxf5 gxf5 {[%csl Ge4] , and Black has full
control over e4.} 12. b3 Rc8 13. Bd2 Ne4 14. Rc1 e6 {Homm,M (2043) -Heinemann,
T (2441)/Hamburg Junge op 2005 (1)/0-1 , with a nice position for Black in})
6... O-O 7. O-O dxc4 $1 (7... Nbd7 $6 {is a bit imprecise in view of} 8. cxd5
$1 {[%csl Gd7] White usually avoids this exchange with the knight still on b8
because it would gain the more active square c6, while now it is a bit
misplaced on d7.} cxd5 9. Qb3 $14 {, with some pressure in Sargissian,G (2602)
-Atalik,S (2560)/ Moscow Aeroflot op-A 2005 (6)/1/2-1/2}) 8. Bxc4 Nbd7 {
[%cal Ge7e5] This is the drawback of developing the knight to e2. Black is
able to continue opening the centre with e7-e5.} 9. e4 (9. f4 $2 {looks bad
because Black hits in the centre anyway.} c5 $1) 9... b5 $1 {[%csl Ye4][%cal
Gb5b4] A nice intermediate move. White is forced to retreat the bishop to d3
to defend the e4-pawn.} (9... e5 {is also playable. In the notes of his game,
Atalik says he considered to play this way, but overestimated} 10. f4 {for
White, since after} exd4 11. Qxd4 Nb6 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Bb3 Bg4 $132 {Black
has enough counterplay, and further white advances in the centre would create
weak squares.}) 10. Bd3 e5 $1 {Black has already equalized, and after} 11. Bg5
$2 {he even took the initiative.} exd4 12. Nxd4 Ne5 13. Bc2 $2 (13. Be2 $142 b4
14. Na4 h6 $15) 13... Qb6 $17 {[%cal Yf8d8] ;Siegel,M-Pavey,M/Manhattan CC-ch
1955/56 1955 (13)/0-1}) (5. h4 {This extravagant move can be found in more
than one of Rapport's games, and although we have seen similar ideas in almost
any opening nowadays, I don't think it is really dangerous here, as White has
already lost the idea of Bh6, which is the main purpose of this kind of
operation.} Bg7 6. Nh3 {[%cal Yh3f4]} Bxh3 $1 7. Rxh3 h5 {After this exchange
Black does not have too many problems finishing development, despite White's
attempts to get something out of his set-up.} 8. Qb3 Qd7 9. Bd2 e6 10. O-O-O
Qc7 $1 11. Kb1 Nbd7 12. Rc1 Qb6 13. Qa3 a5 $1 {[%cal Gb6b4]} 14. cxd5 exd5 15.
e4 $5 dxe4 16. Re3 {[%csl Ye3] Rapport finally managed to find a purpose for
this rook, but Black is just in time to avoid any danger with} Bf8 $1 17. Qa4
Bb4 18. Nxe4 O-O $17 {Rapport,R (2747)-Yu,Y (2752)/Saint Louis Blitz blitz
2019 (12)/0-1}) 5... Bg7 6. Be2 {White has a wide range of options in this
position, although he mostly goes for normal development. It is important to
know how to play against the sidelines, as they are not that dangerous, but
usually contain one or two positional tricks, which aim to leave White with an
easier game.} (6. Bd3 {the bishop is more active on d3, but this is not so
important, as Black may even transpose to one of our main options if he wants
to.} O-O 7. O-O Bg4 {This is an option if Black wants to have a long game.} (
